<li>Alignment of the nucleotide sequences of the UlaR operator sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996803" target="_blank">14996803</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sequence alignment of the four proposed operators allowed us to deÔ¨Åne a consensus motif , consisting of an inverted-repeat present in each one , which might be recognized by the UlaR repressor ( Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996803" target="_blank">14996803</a>]<br></li>
<li>The arrows indicate the inverted-repeat recognized by UlaR DISCUSSION The occurrence of multiple repressor binding sites is a rather common phenomenon , as illustrated by the models of the gal operon ( 15 , 19 ) or the araBAD operon ( 9 , 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996803" target="_blank">14996803</a>]<br></li>
<li>Electrophoretic mobility shift assays with puriÔ¨Åed UlaR protein and promoter deletion analyses revealed a conserved sequence , present in each of the four operators , acting as a UlaR binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996803" target="_blank">14996803</a>]<br></li>
<li>A characteristic of the negative control by UlaR is that the protein may bind cooperatively to every one of the four operators organized in two pairs separated by 187 bp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14996803" target="_blank">14996803</a>]<br></li>
